@node FILEREQ "File requester"

File requester (from asl.library) is opened when ColourLock is launched from
Workbench or from Shell but without PALETTE parameter. It allows You to
select picture from which palette will be grabbed. Not all files are shown
in the requester. Files are filtered by determining datatype class they
belongs to. See also @{"filetypes" LINK FILETYPES}.

@endnode
@node FILETYPES "File types"

ColourLock uses datatypes to recognize picture files and grab palette from
them. But these are some problems:

- HiColor and TrueColor pictures. These don't contain palette. v40
  picture.datatype always tell that these have 256 colours, and returns
  render palette. v43 of picture.datatype can manage 24-bit data. I think
  this makes no sense to use render palettes from datatype. So there are two
  things filtering >256 colours pictures. Firstly all JPEG files are
  rejected. These are always 24-bit. This is done by datatype ID checking.
  All "jpeg" or "jfif" ID's are rejected. If You use v43 picture.datatype
  PDTA_NumColors attribute is checked and a picture is not used if the 
  attribute value is greater than 256. The problem is with PNG files (and
  other that can be both colormapped or Hi/True color) and v40
  picture.datatype. In this case datatype-render palette will be used.
  
- Icons. Amiga icon datatype always returns palette of WB screen. This makes
  no sense to set it again. So filtering should be added, but currently it
  isn't.

- IFF ILBM palettes. Datatype refuse to create DTObject if there is no BODY
  chunk in the file.This is the case for palettes written by DPaint or
  PPaint. So ILBM files are parsed with iffparse.library.
  
ColourLock have been tested succesfully with this datatype system:

# datatypes.library 39.11

# picture.datatype 39.14

# akGIF.datatype 43.8
# akPNG.datatype 43.160
# akJFIF.datatype 43.160 (pictures are rejected)
# bmp.datatype 39.4
# HWGPOST.datatype 40.2
# ico.datatype 42.1
# ilbm.datatype 39.9
# info.datatype 39.1 (always return WB palette)
# pcx.datatype 42.1

Let me know if You test ColourLock with other datatypes, or versions.

@endnode
@node FAQ "ColourLock FAQ"

Frequently Asked Questions

@{b}I've tried to grab palette from NewIcon. It doesn't work.@{ub}

Amiga icon datatype always returns WB palette. If You really need palette
grabbed from NewIcon read it with Iconian and write as IFF ILBM palette.

@{b}I have an gfx card. Need I use ColourLock?@{ub}

It depends on display mode of WB screen. If it is 8-bit this is a
colormapped mode similar to AGA (but don't mess it with chunky - planar
difference!). It means every pixel data contains colour number in a palette
(colour table).  So ColourLock will be useful to You too. If You use 16 or
24 bit screen for Your WB this is a direct-colour mode. Every pixel data
contains RGB values and the screen hasn't a color table. ColourLock is
needed only for colourmapped screens. It is possible that ColourLock is
useful also with 16/24 bit screens to avoid problems with MUI (see below).
But I haven't a gfx card so I can't say more about it.

@{b}I have problems with MUI colours. "Halfshine", "halfshadow" and "mark" are
completely messed up! @{ub}

MUI seems to not allocate colours at all. It always uses pens 4-7 for
rendering, and expects to find MWB-like colours there. So You should
prepare proper palette. These needn't to be exactly MWB colours, e.g. I use
light grey-blue for colour 6 and light grey-green for colour 7. IMHO looks
better than original:-).

@endnode
